1
00:00:00,267 --> 00:00:29,329
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble.

2
00:00:29,646 --> 00:00:31,169
and fully self-awakened.

3
00:00:32,890 --> 00:00:40,018
What I've done here is put a few questions together since they just revolve around the same sort of theme.

4
00:00:40,598 --> 00:00:47,646
So the first one, the questions are, what does causes and conditions mean?

5
00:00:50,509 --> 00:00:55,215
The next one was, what about and what about free will?

6
00:00:56,343 --> 00:01:03,978
And then there is, why is it we clean, how is it, or why is it we clean our karma when we practice vipassana?

7
00:01:06,222 --> 00:01:12,495
And sort of as a side issue to that, the term spiritual bypassing.

8
00:01:12,474 --> 00:01:41,621
does that mean that one unskillfully uses the practice to avoid unpleasant feelings and emotions and if so what might some of the more subtle indicators of this be when it occurs yeah so this all revolves around you know the Buddha's teaching about karma and the main

9
00:01:41,921 --> 00:02:06,579
teaching is really around dependent origination because that's how we create karma karma here meaning our conditioning our own personal conditioning and this this conditioning is always within conditions it's never we're never completely separate from the world around us or the relationships around us or so it's always a sort of negotiated

10
00:02:07,031 --> 00:02:29,343
process where we're working in a situation from a particular intention and you haven't a clue what's going to happen once you activate it the general rule of course is that if you do something wholesome something wholesome arises out of it and if you do something unwholesome unwholesomeness arises

11
00:02:30,877 --> 00:02:55,467
so uh causes and conditions uh that was of course what um drew sariputta to the buddha when he met uh one of the five companions that the buddha was with before his liberation asaji and when he said was your teacher teach he said well where there's a where there's a cause there's a reason for it i'm paraphrasing and uh and that somehow clicked with

12
00:02:55,750 --> 00:02:58,715
Sariputta, who then went off to search for the Buddha.

13
00:02:59,635 --> 00:03:01,579
So everything is conditioned.

14
00:03:02,259 --> 00:03:16,281
So how is it in all these conditions, which have their own causes, and remember there are two types of causes, put as the iddha-pachayatā, I think that's what it's called, the law of this and that.

15
00:03:18,304 --> 00:03:24,693
When that happened in the past, this happens now, and when that didn't happen, this didn't happen now.

16
00:03:25,282 --> 00:03:32,229
And then of course there's the immediate presence contingency because this happens now, this happens because this doesn't happen.

17
00:03:32,248 --> 00:03:32,949
This doesn't happen.

18
00:03:33,770 --> 00:03:35,451
So my usual example is the group.

19
00:03:35,472 --> 00:03:37,813
You see, you've all come from different pasts.

20
00:03:37,854 --> 00:03:39,997
You've all come from different places, different reasons.

21
00:03:40,637 --> 00:03:44,420
And once we are here, we create something just out of that, you see.

22
00:03:45,081 --> 00:03:50,546
And then when you're here, of course, there's this relationship going on all the time.

23
00:03:51,116 --> 00:03:53,522
both with you and the meditation and you with others.

24
00:03:54,205 --> 00:04:03,490
So causes and conditions are all mixed up in a process which is happening in the present affected by the past.

25
00:04:05,191 --> 00:04:11,741
And you can't separate that because if you think everything is from the past, then you're into fate.

26
00:04:12,924 --> 00:04:21,899
And I suppose logically, as one writer said, if everything was just cause and effect from the past, where would creativity come from?

27
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:24,262
It would be a sort of repetitive process.

28
00:04:24,242 --> 00:04:49,709
universe or whatever cosmos but on the other hand if there's no past if everything happens just spontaneous they're not have you have some sort of chaos so there's the creativity things come together from the past to create a present moment and that's the creative moment that is and you can see it in our in our sort of round of politics you know

29
00:04:50,163 --> 00:04:54,247
how the world slowly moves towards psychosis and a war.

30
00:04:55,026 --> 00:04:59,091
And then there's a healing period and you're all right for about 20, 30 years.

31
00:04:59,752 --> 00:05:02,694
And then it all starts moving up again into this catastrophe.

32
00:05:04,014 --> 00:05:08,819
So it happens both in the wider scale and of course in ourselves also.

33
00:05:09,079 --> 00:05:20,170
So if you take the view that causes and conditions determine everything, then you're on the far side of free will, which is

34
00:05:20,452 --> 00:05:43,913
fate everything's conditioned right and there are there were people in the buddha's time who thought that you know they taught that everything's determined so why bother it'll just happen see uh i don't know i don't have any modern philosopher who has that extreme view i'm sure there are somewhere hidden on youtube

35
00:05:44,298 --> 00:05:48,202
And then there's... And the other side is, of course, complete free will.

36
00:05:48,483 --> 00:05:53,629
You have complete... And the teacher of that, of course, was Jean-Paul Sartre.

37
00:05:54,130 --> 00:05:58,576
He said every conscious moment you have the freedom of choice.

38
00:05:58,776 --> 00:05:59,838
You're completely free.

39
00:06:00,259 --> 00:06:06,026
But what stops you, of course, is your neuroses, your hangouts, your et cetera, et cetera.

40
00:06:08,029 --> 00:06:09,732
And that wouldn't...

41
00:06:09,752 --> 00:06:13,697
I mean, in that sense, in that very, very narrow sense that...

42
00:06:14,048 --> 00:06:38,858
each and every moment presents us with an opportunity for choice then you know we could say that there is some sort of free will but Buddhism is normally put in this middle place which they call compatibilism and so obviously some of our lives is fated just you know the fact that you're born into the society you've got a language which gives you certain structures and

43
00:06:39,057 --> 00:07:05,487
you know you can't get out of that it's very difficult you have to learn another language you have to enculturate you have to go native into another language to realize how caught up we are in our own concepts and ideas i mean one obvious example is the way the west is so individual how we're you know it's like it's you know i did it my way whereas in the east they don't see themselves that they see themselves very much as part of a group and that's why

44
00:07:05,922 --> 00:07:10,012
We find, you know, the Japanese and Chinese quite difficult to understand.

45
00:07:11,093 --> 00:07:22,682
We think they're just, you know, being manipulated or following the group, you know, but they're very much a family centred, group centred, nation centred.

46
00:07:23,944 --> 00:07:27,490
So that for me is a very obvious difference.

47
00:07:27,509 --> 00:07:31,336
So there's a part of us which is already set.

48
00:07:32,096 --> 00:07:36,463
It's just part of our conditioning in the world, the society, etc.

49
00:07:37,704 --> 00:07:41,129
And there's a part of us which has a choice.

50
00:07:41,189 --> 00:07:44,754
Now, here we've got to be careful because

51
00:07:45,038 --> 00:08:14,572
when you see somebody uh you know going down the biscuit aisle thinking that they have a choice you know as to what they're going to choose i mean i've done this myself where you go in and you think right i'm going to have something new you know i'm fed up with chocolate biscuits so you go all the way along 100 biscuits at tesco's and then and you keep coming back and you start centering on chocolate biscuits and in the end you think to hell with it i'll have my job

52
00:08:16,088 --> 00:08:18,310
So I like the conditioning is so great.

53
00:08:19,632 --> 00:08:22,175
I'm not I'm not particularly chocolate biscuits.

54
00:08:22,216 --> 00:08:29,285
I once talked about coffee like that and suddenly got all this coffee arriving.

55
00:08:29,305 --> 00:08:40,559
So that that when we're deluded, the idea of choice is is obviously something that consumerism works on.

56
00:08:41,029 --> 00:09:06,565
uh the delusion that you have a choice that in fact you know you're the one who chooses this particular piece of clothing you know that it hasn't been chosen for you and of course that's that's a from a Buddhist point of view that's a very delusive area because uh it's it's being manipulated by your desires your attachments your following of the crowd being one of the many all that sort of stuff you know

57
00:09:06,544 --> 00:09:14,000
But once we start meditating, then this faculty of discrimination comes in.

58
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:19,373
Now, what discrimination does is it's looking at choices that come up within us.

59
00:09:19,774 --> 00:09:49,697
uh from the position of uh of the path you know where are we heading from so you you know this business of the aim and the objective so the aim is to get fully liberated from all suffering so the object arises every present moment which is either off the path or on it so uh because of our strong conditioning for certain things uh certain habits certain indulgences and whatnot you know we're always sort of slipping off on these little side roads but

60
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:53,855
But eventually we sort of drag ourselves back and get on the path.

61
00:09:54,697 --> 00:09:58,023
And what does that, of course, is this discrimination.

62
00:09:58,764 --> 00:10:07,517
So you might say that even for somebody who's completely caught up in their desires and whatnot,

63
00:10:08,087 --> 00:10:12,974
there remains some sort of choice or at least the potential of choice.

64
00:10:13,033 --> 00:10:18,660
I mean, they can say no chocolate biscuits today, you know, but it's difficult.

65
00:10:19,361 --> 00:10:29,234
And then there are those of us who are on the path who are dragged by old habits, but this new understanding keeps bringing us back to the path.

66
00:10:30,255 --> 00:10:36,964
So in what way, you know, do we have free will in any extent, you see?

67
00:10:38,091 --> 00:10:39,092
But it doesn't work, does it?

68
00:10:39,614 --> 00:10:45,682
Because once you know where you're going, then the path is set for you.

69
00:10:46,203 --> 00:10:49,048
So it's just like when you go for a walk, you know.

70
00:10:49,067 --> 00:10:51,291
Tomorrow's my day off, by the way.

71
00:10:51,630 --> 00:10:54,475
So I'll probably climb a hill with Mark.

72
00:10:55,096 --> 00:10:56,999
And it depends on the weather.

73
00:10:57,019 --> 00:10:59,543
And of course, once we've decided on a hill, that's it.

74
00:11:00,104 --> 00:11:03,808
It's not as though you go halfway up and say, hold on, let's do the other hill.

75
00:11:04,068 --> 00:11:05,331
You know what I mean?

76
00:11:05,311 --> 00:11:08,335
Like you set your pace and you stay on that path.

77
00:11:08,394 --> 00:11:18,068
If you come off piste, then there's a chance of getting lost in all the other side little side routes, but you keep coming back to the path you want to get to the top.

78
00:11:19,711 --> 00:11:29,745
So in a sense, I would argue that the idea of choice is, I mean, it's there.

79
00:11:29,785 --> 00:11:32,549
You can choose not to be on the path.

80
00:11:33,340 --> 00:11:43,216
But in terms of where your heart is, where your direction is, where your objective is or your aim is, you don't have much of a choice.

81
00:11:43,518 --> 00:11:45,822
It's like this is the path.

82
00:11:45,841 --> 00:11:46,623
I've got to stay on it.

83
00:11:47,684 --> 00:11:50,570
So for me, it's a funny one.

84
00:11:50,610 --> 00:11:53,154
I try to come off the whole idea of free will.

85
00:11:53,624 --> 00:11:59,414
and just talk about discrimination and what that actually leads us to do.

86
00:11:59,956 --> 00:12:06,668
And then to have the commitment, the understanding comes with the discrimination to know, well, this is what you're going to do.

87
00:12:09,433 --> 00:12:16,628
So part of that clarity, part of that discrimination, of course,

88
00:12:16,878 --> 00:12:26,821
it comes with the purity of the heart because it's the turbulences in the heart, it's the little delusive habits that we have in the heart that keep taking us away.

89
00:12:27,722 --> 00:12:32,793
And so whenever we're meditating and we can see this stuff coming up, irritations,

90
00:12:32,993 --> 00:12:38,285
anxieties, overexcitements, planning, planning, all that sort of stuff.

91
00:12:38,307 --> 00:12:50,277
For us, that's recognizing that these are little devils that sort of sit behind us and keep prodding us and unwittingly often guide our lives without us being fully aware of it.

92
00:12:50,965 --> 00:12:57,094
And so as these come into awareness and we recognize them as unwholesome, we allow them to burn out.

93
00:12:57,836 --> 00:13:02,081
And that's really getting rid of old viparka.

94
00:13:02,383 --> 00:13:07,691
I mean, if we want to be strictly correct, kamma is your action.

95
00:13:08,030 --> 00:13:09,393
The consequence is viparka.

96
00:13:09,653 --> 00:13:13,799
But I know these days we just use the word kamma to mean consequences.

97
00:13:15,163 --> 00:13:19,976
So these are the consequences that are in us, in our own hearts because of past action.

98
00:13:20,578 --> 00:13:23,567
And you can't get rid of them just like that.

99
00:13:23,647 --> 00:13:25,511
You have to allow them to express themselves.

100
00:13:26,065 --> 00:13:35,299
And that's one reason why the meditation is so difficult because, you know, it's 99% purification and 1% chocolate biscuits.

101
00:13:36,402 --> 00:13:37,724
It's like there isn't much.

102
00:13:39,206 --> 00:13:42,532
But as you progress, of course, you get more chocolate biscuits.

103
00:13:44,195 --> 00:13:48,061
Or at least the misery tones down a bit.

104
00:13:48,181 --> 00:13:48,902
That's what we can say.

105
00:13:48,942 --> 00:13:50,605
The misery tones down.

106
00:13:50,585 --> 00:13:58,417
Remember, right to the very end, there's some form of restlessness in the person.

107
00:13:58,437 --> 00:14:06,889
So a lot of our practice is, first of all, releasing this turbulence in the heart, allowing it to manifest.

108
00:14:07,410 --> 00:14:10,095
And the other side is, of course, this discrimination.

109
00:14:10,816 --> 00:14:12,097
And that's the wisdom factor.

110
00:14:12,118 --> 00:14:18,027
That's this satipanya, this intuitive awareness, coming to realize that

111
00:14:18,445 --> 00:14:24,523
that it's not looking at things properly, it's not engaging properly, and that's what's creating the problem.

112
00:14:25,312 --> 00:14:29,557
So there is a process of purification and a process of insight.

113
00:14:30,118 --> 00:14:37,306
And this insight slowly but surely guides us out of those habits that create problems for us.

114
00:14:38,066 --> 00:14:40,288
So that's how it happens.

115
00:14:40,308 --> 00:14:46,014
And remember that these internal turbulences need not come out as memories.

116
00:14:46,154 --> 00:14:47,556
They need not come out as emotions.

117
00:14:47,996 --> 00:14:49,378
They just come out as pain.

118
00:14:49,457 --> 00:14:50,578
They can just come out as pain.

119
00:14:51,120 --> 00:14:51,220
Yeah.

120
00:14:53,528 --> 00:14:54,149
unfortunately.

121
00:14:54,932 --> 00:15:00,787
And when the pain comes out, you know something's gone because, you know, but you haven't a clue what it was.

122
00:15:01,168 --> 00:15:03,553
And the wonderful thing is you don't have to know.

123
00:15:04,537 --> 00:15:07,605
You don't have to, you don't have to do a psychotherapy on yourself, you know.

124
00:15:09,187 --> 00:15:10,490
It's always a waste of time anyway.

125
00:15:10,929 --> 00:15:20,822
I remember when I was going way back and I read all these books, you know, Freud, Jung, Lang, just reading.

126
00:15:20,842 --> 00:15:22,885
And I came to this amazing conclusion.

127
00:15:23,326 --> 00:15:24,107
I always remember this.

128
00:15:24,508 --> 00:15:28,192
I was about 25 and I thought, finally, I know myself.

129
00:15:32,719 --> 00:15:33,179
Yes.

130
00:15:35,062 --> 00:15:35,802
Delusion.

131
00:15:37,201 --> 00:15:46,491
So one of the dangers of the process is what's been known by, I think, yeah, I should have looked it up.

132
00:15:46,511 --> 00:15:46,952
I'm sorry.

133
00:15:47,232 --> 00:15:48,554
His name's Wellwood, I think.

134
00:15:48,815 --> 00:15:49,975
He's a very good writer.

135
00:15:50,616 --> 00:16:00,349
And he was both a psychotherapist, psychiatrist, no, psychotherapist, and a very good meditator, belonging to the Tibetan tradition, I think.

136
00:16:01,070 --> 00:16:05,335
And it was he who coined this phrase, bypassing, spiritual bypassing.

137
00:16:05,787 --> 00:16:11,293
And this happens when you're not really into dukkha.

138
00:16:11,452 --> 00:16:23,144
You're not really, you don't want to, you don't want to sink into proper dukkha, you know, real, real burning, hot, fiery, squeegee suffering, you know.

139
00:16:23,164 --> 00:16:26,548
And so what you do is you distance yourself from it.

140
00:16:27,350 --> 00:16:34,157
And that's this, one of the, you know, one of our mistakes that we make by pointing at it, especially with the noting.

141
00:16:34,136 --> 00:16:39,224
So you say something like, you know, anger, anger, anger, and actually you're pushing it away.

142
00:16:39,344 --> 00:16:41,626
You're keeping it well away over there.

143
00:16:42,528 --> 00:16:46,212
And of course, that doesn't mean to say that it has the opportunity to burn out.

144
00:16:46,953 --> 00:16:50,499
And so it rests there as a sort of dis-ease in the mind.

145
00:16:50,960 --> 00:16:57,328
And all the time, the meditators saying to themselves, you know, I'm liberated from anger.

146
00:16:57,629 --> 00:16:58,951
I never react to anger.

147
00:16:59,831 --> 00:17:02,034
I see it coming and it's, you know, and it's fine.

148
00:17:02,403 --> 00:17:06,426
And I can see it purifying, but actually it's not happening.

149
00:17:07,147 --> 00:17:08,809
See, they're keeping it distant.

150
00:17:09,190 --> 00:17:12,874
And this happens when you're interested in impermanence.

151
00:17:13,094 --> 00:17:14,675
Oh, yes, very good, yeah.

152
00:17:14,695 --> 00:17:15,797
And not me, not mine.

153
00:17:16,116 --> 00:17:27,147
But this not me, not mine is really being used to push things out of consciousness, to keep it in consciousness in a way that you feel comfortable with it.

154
00:17:28,189 --> 00:17:30,672
And what you're not looking at is the reactivity.

155
00:17:31,292 --> 00:17:33,675
which is not wanting to feel this stuff.

156
00:17:34,936 --> 00:17:40,063
So what happens there is that all the stuff is accumulating.

157
00:17:40,083 --> 00:17:44,208
Because remember, every time you sit, you're beckoning the heart to manifest itself.

158
00:17:44,268 --> 00:17:47,491
Yeah, because you've pulled off the suppressive measures.

159
00:17:48,073 --> 00:17:50,556
You found this observation post inside yourself.

160
00:17:50,675 --> 00:17:56,102
It's this place where you're above the mind or should we say slightly beyond it.

161
00:17:56,082 --> 00:18:07,260
And so you're not reacting, you're not reacting with fear or aversion, and therefore the heart feels free to begin to manifest.

162
00:18:08,702 --> 00:18:13,652
And in so doing, it can come up to such a point where the meditator keeps pushing back.

163
00:18:14,593 --> 00:18:20,502
In the Mahasi tradition you see, and in fact in Theravada in general,

164
00:18:20,752 --> 00:18:28,346
Just as we chant in the morning, it's impermanence, suffering and not self.

165
00:18:28,405 --> 00:18:29,468
That's the process, you see.

166
00:18:30,349 --> 00:18:36,400
And the reason why impermanence is put first is because it's a way into the other two.

167
00:18:36,817 --> 00:18:40,903
What arises and passes away radically can be seen as having no substance.

168
00:18:41,403 --> 00:18:41,964
It's not real.

169
00:18:42,746 --> 00:18:44,948
It's an attack.

170
00:18:44,969 --> 00:18:53,298
And what arises and passes away, it makes it useless to grasp onto something, to attach anything, because it's gone anyway.

171
00:18:53,338 --> 00:18:57,444
It's only by dint of force that you hold onto things.

172
00:18:57,464 --> 00:19:02,411
So anicca is a way into seeing these two, but not actually experiencing them.

173
00:19:02,431 --> 00:19:03,972
That's your problem.

174
00:19:03,952 --> 00:19:13,142
See, you see it, you can see it from one angle, but in a sense you've got to also see it from the angle of anatta and the angle of dukkha.

175
00:19:13,162 --> 00:19:17,926
The angle of anatta is, of course, to see you're not in control, you don't have full control.

176
00:19:18,847 --> 00:19:25,875
So that's the opening part of the discourse on the anatta, lakha and asutta, the discourse on the characteristic of not-self.

177
00:19:26,895 --> 00:19:33,521
The first question is, you know, if this were my body, I'm paraphrasing, could I make it

178
00:19:33,501 --> 00:19:37,507
you know, grow taller, have more hair, things like that, you see.

179
00:19:37,906 --> 00:19:40,029
And the question is, and they say, oh no, Bhante, no.

180
00:19:40,430 --> 00:19:48,019
So you can see there's limitations of power over the body, the heart, the mind, etc.

181
00:19:48,740 --> 00:19:57,430
So that limitation of a lack of control is one of the sources of insight from the point of view of anatta, right?

182
00:19:57,470 --> 00:20:00,094
Not from the point of view of anicca, right?

183
00:20:00,114 --> 00:20:01,315
Although it might hint at it.

184
00:20:03,269 --> 00:20:17,968
And when it comes to dukkha, that's what the dependent origination is pointing us to, to this whole business of reactivity, of how we react to things and unwittingly cause ourselves more and more problems.

185
00:20:18,368 --> 00:20:29,943
So that little escape route between vedana, feeling, and tanha, which is that movement towards it of wanting it or pushing it away.

186
00:20:30,424 --> 00:20:30,525
Yeah.

187
00:20:31,298 --> 00:20:33,421
Now, there's another question here.

188
00:20:35,704 --> 00:20:36,125
Where was it?

189
00:20:36,226 --> 00:20:36,846
Oh, yeah.

190
00:20:37,548 --> 00:20:38,829
Oh, that comes up a bit later.

191
00:20:39,009 --> 00:20:40,192
I'll come back to that.

192
00:20:41,913 --> 00:20:44,759
Well, no, this is a good time to do it.

193
00:20:45,559 --> 00:20:46,741
I've got it in blue, you see.

194
00:20:47,482 --> 00:20:50,667
I'm answering orange at the moment.

195
00:20:51,127 --> 00:20:56,817
In the discourse on the Satipaṭṭhāna, he has this recurrent phrase,

